<subSubSection box="[198,1249,2003,2030]" pageId="15" pageNumber="61" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1152,2030]" box="[198,1249,2003,2030]" pageId="15" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,339,2003,2029]" pageId="15" pageNumber="61">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named in reference to the complete lack of wings in the male of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="62" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,151,332]" pageId="16" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,320,151,177]" pageId="16" pageNumber="62">Remarks.</emphasis>
This unusual species is the first example of a complete aptery in the males of the 
<taxonomicName box="[151,348,190,216]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phaneropterinae">Phaneropterinae</taxonomicName>
. Despite the complete lack of wings, the tympanal organs on the front tibia in these insects are developed normally. The lack of stridulatory organs in 
<taxonomicName box="[857,969,229,254]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Brinckiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aptera">
<emphasis box="[857,969,229,254]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="62">B. aptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
raises the question of how the females find males during the breeding season, and whether an alternative form of communication (e.g., tremulation or pheromonal communication) might have evolved in this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
